<li id="c21">
  <div class="cx" id="cx51079029">
   <h5> <a class="de">&nbsp;</a><span class="cu">...while you do touch on the problem...</span>


<span class="crd ntb">(<a href="/comments/1231497/51079029#c21?mode=alone;showrate=1#c21">0+ / 0-</a>)</span>
  </h5>

  
  


  

  <div class="ct">
  
<p>...that capitalism ALWAYS does whatever it can to make the most profit possible, the minimum wage currently is a huge problem.</p>
<p>We all had minimum wage jobs...and they were entry jobs. The thing is the minimum wage today would have to be $9.47 per hour to equal the buying power of what minimum wage was "worth" when it was $2.00 an hour.</p>
<p>Another HUGE problem is a legal maneuver that George Bush got through = changing the status of workers. In our day, if you worked more than 40 hours per week, you got overtime pay which was 1.5 times as much as regular pay. NOW they have simply changed what workers are called. They are called "representatives" or "associates." Why? Because the law then says they aren't hourly employees any more...they are "management." And management is a "salaried" position meaning it doesn't matter how many hours you work...you don't get overtime pay.</p>
<p>The world of working minimum wage jobs is NOTHING like it was when you and I had those jobs. We could actually do things like save. I worked all through high school and was able to save enough to pay for my first year's college tuition, dorm and text books. Sure I went to a public college, but still I was able to save that much money over a three year period of time...and that is because what minimum wage paid in comparison to what things cost.</p>
<p>If the current minimum wage was $9.47 per hour and people were getting time-and-a-half pay if they worked over 40 hours a week then more folks COULD live and save and get a foothold going in another direction. Now minimum wage earners don't have the "luxury" we had...</p>
